THE RISK:
{
 "id": "prelet-pipeline-lockout",
 "title": "The growth the CAGR promises was electrically specified before launch day — Year 1 can only sell into the installed base",
 "narrative": "Nine percent CAGR reads as a tailwind: new halls, new racks, new PDU line items every quarter of Year 1. But new-build DC electrical procurement is locked at design freeze, and with long-lead power equipment (transformers, switchgear) now booked years out, operators are locking entire electrical BOMs — PDUs riding along — far earlier than the 12–24-month window the ledger's own crossCheck uses to justify its ceiling. Every megawatt that energizes during the venture's first 12 months had its rack-power vendor chosen while the venture was still pre-launch. That leaves Year-1 demand confined to retrofit, refresh and expansion churn in the installed base — a materially smaller and slower pool than 'the market' — while the model applies its 1% to the whole SAM as if new-build spend were reachable on the venture's clock.",
 "category": "model-structure",
 "targetNodes": [
  "obtainableFactor"
 ],
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "New-build electrical BOMs for capacity energizing in the venture's Year 1 were specified at design freeze, before the venture existed as a qualified vendor; the ledger's own crossCheck concedes gear is 'locked 12–24mo before fit-out' and current long-lead conditions push lock-in earlier still",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:obtainableFactor",
    "profile:Stage"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "The market's growth is concentrated in exactly this pre-committed new-build pipeline (the substance of the 9% CAGR), so the contestable Year-1 pool is the installed base's refresh cycle — and what standalone PDU procurement evidence exists shows small, sometimes sole-sourced lots with 1–2 bidders, not open bake-offs",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:shape.cagr",
    "digest:obtainable-benchmark#c12"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "Generic obtainable-share benchmarks (1% Year 1) assume the full SAM is time-reachable; no DC-hardware-specific benchmark exists that discounts for procurement lock-in, so the model has no mechanism to encode it",
   "refs": [
    "digest:obtainable-benchmark#c0",
    "digest:obtainable-benchmark#c2"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "obtainableFactor applied to the full SAM double-counts pre-committed new-build spend as reachable; the truly contestable Year-1 share sits at or below the band floor",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:obtainableFactor"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "The founder's plan treats the CAGR as an accelerant and 1% as conservative precisely because the market is growing — 'we only need a tiny slice of a rising tide.' The trap is that the rising portion of the tide is the least reachable portion on a 12-month clock; the model has no node that separates committed-pipeline demand from contestable demand, so nothing in the ledger flags it.",
 "expectedObviousness": "medium",
 "falsifier": "Documented cases of CE new-build data centers running competitive rack-PDU selection within 6 months of fit-out (i.e., inside the venture's selling window), or an operator confirming PDUs are procured late as a commodity line decoupled from the electrical design freeze.",
 "likelihood": {
  "value": 0.55,
  "rationale": "Early electrical lock-in for new builds is well-documented industry behavior and the ledger's own crossCheck relies on a 12–24-month version of it; the offsetting uncertainty is how much PDU spend is genuinely late-cycle commodity purchasing versus BOM-committed — unquantified in every retrieved source. [evidence revision: The core premise of early electrical lock-in for new builds is now strongly corroborated by multiple independent sources (exceeding the 12-24mo window the ledger uses), which modestly strengthens the hypothesis. However, the crucial unquantified gap remains: no retrieved evidence establishes whether rack PDUs specifically ride the frozen BOM or are procured late as a commodity line — the PDU sourcing guides describe RFQ processes without timing relative to design freeze. This keeps the likelihood near coin-flip; the trigger is well-supported but the PDU-coupling link that makes it consequential is still inferential.]",
  "basis": "evidence",
  "revisedFrom": 0.5
 },
 "perturbation": [
  {
   "nodeId": "obtainableFactor",
   "op": "set",
   "value": 0.005,
   "note": "Year-1 capture limited to installed-base retrofit/refresh; new-build pipeline pre-committed before launch"
  }
 ],
 "indicators": [
  {
   "signal": "Stage at which rack-PDU vendor is fixed in CE fit-out tenders (bundled at design freeze vs late separate lot)",
   "where": "TED tender documents for DE/NL data-center fit-outs; fit-out contractors' bid packages",
   "threshold": "PDU line bundled into general-electrical packages in ≥3 of 4 sampled tenders",
   "updates": "increases"
  },
  {
   "signal": "Pre-let percentages and long-lead procurement commentary for CE capacity additions",
   "where": "Operator and hyperscaler capex calls (Equinix, Digital Realty quarterly); Vertiv/Schneider backlog commentary",
   "threshold": "Pre-let >80% with electrical packages cited as booked >18 months out",
   "updates": "increases"
  }
 ],
 "mitigations": [
  {
   "action": "Map the 2026–27 CE new-build pipeline by procurement stage (design freeze reached? electrical package awarded?) to quantify the actually-contestable Year-1 pool",
   "type": "information",
   "voiNodeId": "obtainableFactor",
   "note": "Separates committed from contestable SAM — the distinction the funnel lacks"
  },
  {
   "action": "Target the installed-base refresh cycle explicitly: build the launch offer around drop-in replacement and retrofit economics (metering upgrades, DCIM integration) rather than new-build spec wins",
   "type": "strategic",
   "voiNodeId": null,
   "note": null
  }
 ],
 "evidenceStatus": "corroborated",
 "evidence": [
  {
   "title": "Data Center Electrical Procurement: Why the Order Has to Come Before the Design",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "Build.inc",
   "date": "2026-06-22",
   "excerpt": "Power transformer lead times from major manufacturers have reached 48 to 60 months. Generator step-up transformers average 144 weeks. Tier 1 suppliers -- ABB, Siemens Energy, Hitachi Energy -- have backlogs extending to 2030 and beyond. A developer who sequences procurement conventionally and targets energization in 2028 has already missed the window.",
   "url": "https://build.inc/insights/data-center-electrical-procurement-sequence-workflow",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "From Electrical Design to Energization",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "Construction Business Outlook",
   "date": "2026-04-20",
   "excerpt": "the schedule can be effectively lost before a single foundation is poured...because a transformer with a 65-week lead time wasn't released before the topology was finalized. Contractors who consistently deliver these programs on time have stopped treating electrical planning as a downstream task.",
   "url": "https://constructionbusinessoutlook.com/from-electrical-design-to-energization/",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "Electrical Equipment Lead Time Index",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "VAWN",
   "date": "2026-06-02",
   "excerpt": "Power / substation transformer 128 weeks ↑ Elevating; Generator step-up (GSU) transformer 144 weeks ↑ Elevating; Medium-voltage switchgear 44 weeks. Panelboards 15-23 weeks; Circuit breakers (commodity) In stock.",
   "url": "https://usevawn.com/resources/electrical-equipment-lead-times/",
   "attached": true
  }
 ],
 "stances": [
  {
   "url": "https://build.inc/insights/data-center-electrical-procurement-sequence-workflow",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "The conventional development sequence treats electrical equipment procurement as a downstream task: finish design, secure permits, then buy the gear. For data centers in 2026, that sequence is obsolete. Power transformer lead times from major manufacturers have reached 48 to 60 months."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://constructionbusinessoutlook.com/from-electrical-design-to-energization/",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "the schedule can be effectively lost before a single foundation is poured, not because of labor, weather, or permitting, but because a transformer with a 65-week lead time wasn't released before the topology was finalized"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.irecruit.co/insights/data-center-owners-design-management-de-risk-multi-phase-builds",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "owners cut risk by locking the basis of design early, tying equipment releases to design gates"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://usevawn.com/resources/electrical-equipment-lead-times/",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "Power / substation transformer\n\n128 weeks\n\n↑ Elevating"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.htnxt.com/page/How-to-Select-a-Smart-PDU-Supplier-for-Data-Centers:-A-Technical-Buyers-Guide-(2026).html",
   "stance": "silent",
   "quote": "Procurement professionals must evaluate vendors not only on technical specifications but also on real-world deployment track records, certifications, and support capabilities."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.idcpdu.com/news/industry-news/pdu-lead-time-and-production-factors-in-custom-orders.html",
   "stance": "silent",
   "quote": "Custom PDU orders often take longer than buyers expect because lead time depends on far more than basic electrical ratings."
  }
 ]
}

